obile-event/cost`, `v2/month/mobile-events/mobile-day/mobile-event/date`, `v2/month/mobile-events/mobile-day/mobile-event/date/meta`, `v2/month/mobile-events/mobile-day/mobile-event/featured-image`, `v2/month/mobile-events/mobile-day/mobile-event/title`, `v2/month/mobile-events/mobile-day/more-events`, `v2/month/mobile-events/nav`, `v2/month/mobile-events/nav/next-disabled`, `v2/month/mobile-events/nav/next`, `v2/month/mobile-events/nav/prev-disabled`, `v2/month/mobile-events/nav/prev`, `v2/month/mobile-events/nav/today`, `v2/month/top-bar`, `v2/month/top-bar/datepicker`, `v2/not-found`</li>\n<li><strong>Language:</strong><kbd>2 new strings added, 169 updated, 1 fuzzied, and 0 obsoleted</kbd></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/the-events-calendar-5-0-0/\">The Events Calendar 5.0.0</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"\n		\n		\n				\n		\n				\n\n		\n				\n								\n										\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:32:\"Featured Calendar: Sierra Nevada\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/featured-calendar-sierra-nevada/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 15 Jan 2020 19:14:56 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Articles\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1961549\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:573:\"<p>Up in Northern California, above Sacramento, is the town of Chico. It may be a relatively small place, but it&#8217;s home to the Sierra Nevada brewery. What started as a hand-built brewhouse in 1980 is now a household name that&#8217;s expanded to both coasts and is recognized as a pioneer in the craft beer movement.&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/featured-calendar-sierra-nevada/\">Featured Calendar: Sierra Nevada</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Geoff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12126:\"<p>Up in Northern California, above Sacramento, is the town of Chico. It may be a relatively small place, but it&#8217;s home to the <a href=\"https://sierranevada.com\">Sierra Nevada brewery</a>. What started as a hand-built brewhouse in 1980 is now a household name that&#8217;s expanded to both coasts and is recognized as a pioneer in the craft beer movement.</p>\n<p>What does craft beer have to do with calendars? Sierra Nevada regularly hosts musical acts and <a href=\"https://sierranevada.com/events/\">uses The Events Calendar to display them</a> on their website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-1961561 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar.jpg\" alt=\"Screenshot of the main calendar page of the Sierra Nevada website.\" width=\"1565\" height=\"2355\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar.jpg 1565w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-56x85.jpg 56w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-768x1156.jpg 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-665x1001.jpg 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-430x647.jpg 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-645x971.jpg 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-1068x1607.jpg 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-460x692.jpg 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-300x451.jpg 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-532x800.jpg 532w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-calendar-500x752.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1565px) 100vw, 1565px\" /></p>\n<p>Sierra Nevada&#8217;s calendar is noteworthy because it&#8217;s a perfect example of The Event Calendar&#8217;s flexibility. In fact, the calendar hardly resembles The Events Calendar&#8217;s default design and you may never have guessed that they&#8217;re actually using the plugin.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s look at the most notable ways Sierra Nevada has brewed a calendar that&#8217;s as appealing as their beer.</p>\n<h2>The calendar page</h2>\n<p>First impressions are important, right? Well, Sierra Nevada wastes no time showing off a gorgeous calendar.</p>\n<p>The first thing you may notice is the slider on the main calendar page. That&#8217;s a nice touch because it cycles through upcoming featured events before you even reach the calendar.</p>\n<p>How did they do it? The site uses the <a href=\"https://sierranevada.com/events/\">MX theme for WordPress</a> which not only provides page-building features courtesy of <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/visualcomposer/\">Visual Composer</a>, but integrates with popular WordPress slider plugins, including <a href=\"https://codecanyon.net/item/layerslider-responsive-wordpress-slider-plugin/1362246\">LayerSlider</a> and <a href=\"https://revolution.themepunch.com\">Slider Revolution</a>. That allows Sierra Nevada to create a custom page that uses a slider at the top of the page and embed The Events Calendar in the main area.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s the thing about The Events Calendar. Sure, it makes a page for your calendar, but it also lets you <a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/934573-Inserting-Calendar-Content-into-Posts-or-Pages\">add the calendar to any WordPress page or post</a>.</p>\n<h2>The event page</h2>\n<p>Click through to any event on the Sierra Nevada site and you&#8217;ll be greeted with amazing photography. This is another shout out to the MX theme they are using because that&#8217;s how they are able to create a banner like that.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1961562\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event.jpg\" alt=\"Screenshot of an event on the Sierra Nevada website.\" width=\"1565\" height=\"1362\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event.jpg 1565w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-98x85.jpg 98w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-300x261.jpg 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-768x668.jpg 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-665x579.jpg 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-430x374.jpg 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-645x561.jpg 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-1068x929.jpg 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-460x400.jpg 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-600x522.jpg 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-event-500x435.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1565px) 100vw, 1565px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, that&#8217;s how the entire event page is created. Because MX includes Visual Composer, they are able to build a custom layout on a page-by-page (or, in this case, event-by-event) basis. They&#8217;ve added a sidebar that neatly displays event information next to the main content that gives more in-depth details.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1961572\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue.png\" alt=\"Screenshot of an event footer showing more events at the same venue.\" width=\"2328\" height=\"1810\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue.png 2328w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-109x85.png 109w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-300x233.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-768x597.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-665x517.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-430x334.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-645x501.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-2000x1555.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-1068x830.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-460x358.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-1602x1246.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-600x466.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-venue-500x389.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2328px) 100vw, 2328px\" /></p>\n<p>The other interesting thing is how the event page also displays other events happening at the same location. <a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/750833-Venue-and-Organizer-pages\">Events Calendar Pro creates pages for each venue</a> that list the events happening there, but they are not integrated into the event page the way Sierra Nevada has done it. MX includes a lot of useful shortcodes, including one that can display filtered posts. This lets Sierra Nevada display all events that take place at a specific location  very cool!</p>\n<h2>Great ticketing display</h2>\n<p>Notice how tickets can be purchased directly in the banner. Click a button and a modal opens up with ticket options.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1961566\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets.png\" alt=\"The pop-up that displays on a Sierra Nevada event when clicking on the tickets button.\" width=\"2328\" height=\"1916\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets.png 2328w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-103x85.png 103w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-300x247.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-768x632.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-665x547.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-430x354.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-645x531.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-2000x1646.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-1068x879.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-460x379.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-1602x1318.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-600x494.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/01/sierra-nevada-eventbrite-tickets-500x412.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2328px) 100vw, 2328px\" /></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re thinking that&#8217;s not the same ticket design as our Event Tickets plugin, you&#8217;re right! Sierra Nevada is actually using our <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-eventbrite-tickets/\">Eventbrite Tickets add-on</a> to import events from Eventbrite.com into WordPress and display the tickets they created in Eventbrite on the event page. Clicking on a ticket takes you to Eventbrite.com where you can complete the purchase.</p>\n<p>The idea to contain the tickets in a modal is really interesting. It&#8217;s a nice way to hide tickets from view while keeping them super easy to find and purchase.</p>\n<h2>Customizing The Events Calendar yourself</h2>\n<p>Sierra Nevada obviously put a lot effort into their calendar. There are lots of ways to customize the design of it and they are using the features provided by their theme to do it. It&#8217;s a bonus that their theme works so well with The Events Calendar.</p>\n<p>But that&#8217;s not the only choice! You can make The Events Calendar you own in a number of ways:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/451403-The-Events-Calendar-and-the-WordPress-Customizer\"><strong>Use the WordPress Customizer.</strong></a> This might be the easiest way to customize the calendar. By heading to <em>Appearance</em>  <em>Customizer</em> from the WordPress dashboard, you&#8217;ll see a bunch of options that let you change everything from the calendar&#8217;s colors to specific options for each calendar view.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/461733-Basic-font-and-color-changes-with-CSS\"><strong>Use your own CSS.</strong></a> The plugin includes its own stylesheets by default so everything looks great out of the box. However, you can disable those stylesheets and roll your own by adding your custom CSS file to your theme folder.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/153124-Themers-Guide\"><strong>Use custom templates.</strong> </a>Whether you want to make a minor tweak to the calendar layout or overhaul the entire thing, you can use custom templates to override the default views. This requires some coding know-how, but it&#8217;s also the most robust way to create a completely custom look and feel.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Cheers!</h2>\n<p>That&#8217;s a quick look at how Sierra Nevada is using The Events Calendar to showcase events on their website. It&#8217;s awesome to see how far they went to create a custom experience. Perhaps they can add &#8220;craft calendaring&#8221; to their list of accomplishments? <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f914.png\" alt=\"?\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/featured-calendar-sierra-nevada/\">Featured Calendar: Sierra Nevada</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"\n		\n		\n				\n		\n				\n\n		\n				\n								\n										\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"The Events Calendar 4.9.14\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/the-events-calendar-4-9-14/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 15 Jan 2020 14:54:17 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1967781\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:602:\"<p>Hey there! We just shipped a quick maintenance release for The Events Calendar and it features additional compatibility with the WordPress block editor to make creating and editing events a little more polished and enjoyable. Before we jump into the changelogs, it&#8217;s worth mentioning that this round of updates is aMaintenance Release. In other words,&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/the-events-calendar-4-9-14/\">The Events Calendar 4.9.14</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2170:\"<p>Hey there! We just shipped a quick maintenance release for <strong>The Events Calendar</strong> and it features additional compatibility with the WordPress block editor to make creating and editing events a little more polished and enjoyable.</p>\n<p>Before we jump into the changelogs, it&#8217;s worth mentioning that this round of updates is a<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-schedule/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Maintenance Release</a>. In other words, this is a smaller update between major updates and is mostly comprised of bug fixes, tweaks and small, but meaningful improvements. It should be safe to update without breaking changes, but we always suggest backing up your site as you would with any WordPress update.</p>\n<hr />\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Feature</strong> &#8211; We added a Repository filter called <samp>where_meta_related_by_meta</samp> for getting a post by the meta value and associated post. </li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; We have made some modifications to the Freemius code initialization to allow for better data around plugin uninstalls. This gives us a better picture of when and why The Events Calendar is uninstalled so we can continue to make it better and better for you and other folks.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; We adjusted tooltip title styles to be more compatible with the WordPress Twenty Twenty theme.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; The cost field description no longer disappears when using the block editor.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; We resolved an issue so that the organizer field is no longer overriding the theme&#8217;s font when using the block editor.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; The venue block properly receives the correct HTML class now with the block editor.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; We&#8217;ve corrected a missing block issue when switching from block editor to classic editor.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/the-events-calendar-4-9-14/\">The Events Calendar 4.9.14</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"\n		\n		\n				\n		\n				\n\n		\n				\n								\n										\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:65:\"Forget the Fees: Take Control of Ticket Sales on Your Own Website\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:74:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/sell-tickets-for-events-on-your-own-website/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 09 Jan 2020 18:44:59 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Articles\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1915679\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:624:\"<p>Tickets and events. They often go together, not completely unlike the way we expect peanut butter and jelly, bread and butter and ice cream and pickles. The fact is that hosting an event with tickets means that you&#8217;ve gotta sell those tickets. There&#8217;s really no way around it. If attendees require a ticket to get&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/sell-tickets-for-events-on-your-own-website/\">Forget the Fees: Take Control of Ticket Sales on Your Own Website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Geoff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11171:\"<p>Tickets and events. They often go together, not completely unlike the way we expect peanut butter and jelly, bread and butter and ice cream and pickles.</p>\n<p>The fact is that hosting an event with tickets means that you&#8217;ve gotta sell those tickets. There&#8217;s really no way around it. If attendees require a ticket to get in the door, then they&#8217;ll need a way to purchase it.</p>\n<p>The easy solution is to offload that responsibility to a third party and there are great services out there. Think of things like <a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com\">Eventbrite</a> and <a href=\"https://www.ticketfly.com\">Ticketfly</a>. You create an event on their platform and leverage their ticketing tools to take orders. Presto! <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-eventbrite-tickets/\">We even have an add-on</a> that imports events from Eventbrite to The Events Calendar in WordPress.</p>\n<p>But what if it was just as easy to do the same thing on, say, your own website? In an ideal world, you&#8217;d be in full control of your event&#8217;s content and the ticket purchasing experience. And, hey, cutting out fees and revenue sharing would be even more awesome, right?</p>\n<p>Well, that&#8217;s what we&#8217;re going to look at in this post. It is absolutely possible to have all of that (and a bag of chips). There are a few ways to go about it. Let&#8217;s look at those by the level of control they provide.</p>\n<h3>Some control: PayPal</h3>\n<p>If you already have a website, it&#8217;s got to feel redundant to publish event details both there and a ticketing service. It would be a lot easier to publish it once (preferably on your own site) and simply link out to the checkout experience.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s where PayPal&#8217;s strength comes in. It allows you to create a button that you can add to your site. That button takes customers to a PayPal page where they can complete the order.</p>\n<p>The setup is pretty straightforward: There&#8217;s an option to create a button in the Tools menu of your PayPal account. Go there (<a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/buttons/\">here&#8217;s a direct link</a>), tell it what kind of button you want, then drop the code it gives you into your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1915680\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons.png\" alt=\"Showing seven different types of buttons that are available to configure in PayPal, including buy now, subscriptions, donations and others.\" width=\"2350\" height=\"1270\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons.png 2350w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-140x76.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-300x162.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-768x415.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-665x359.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-430x232.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-645x349.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-2000x1081.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-1068x577.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-460x249.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-1602x866.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-600x324.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/paypal-buttons-500x270.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2350px) 100vw, 2350px\" /></p>\n<p>PayPal is great and you should absolutely consider it for your ticket sales. At the same time, you might offer a more complex set of tickets and need more robust features that allow customers to choose between different ticket types (e.g. Early Bird, General Admission, VIP, etc.). You&#8217;ll need a little more control to meet those requirements, so let&#8217;s move on.</p>\n<h3>More control: WooCommerce for WordPress</h3>\n<p>Another way to own your ticket sales is to host the entire purchasing experience on your site.</p>\n<p>Many website platforms offer commerce features so that visitors can make purchases directly from your site. Let&#8217;s look at one in particular: WooCommerce.</p>\n<p>We want to focus on WooCommerce because it&#8217;s built for WordPress and perfectly exemplifies having lots of control. You host the site on your own server. All of your content originates and stays on your site. The functionality for making purchases lives on the site as well. No middlemen!</p>\n<p>While there are many other e-commerce plugins for WordPress, WooCommerce is maintained by Automattic, the company behind WordPress. That gives it more than a slight edge and makes it perhaps the strongest candidate in the bunch.</p>\n<p>The magical thing about WooCommerce is that  in addition to integrating with PayPal  it allows you to take credit card payments. That&#8217;s thanks to integrations with payment gateways like <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/products/stripe/\">Stripe</a>, <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/products/square/\">Square</a>, <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/products/woocommerce-gateway-paypal-powered-by-braintree/\">Braintree</a> and <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/products/authorize-net/\">Authorize.Net</a>, among <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/product-category/woocommerce-extensions/payment-gateways/\">others</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1915694\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions.png\" alt=\"Showing a grid of different payment gateway extensions offered by WooCommerce.\" width=\"1350\" height=\"740\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions.png 1350w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-140x77.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-300x164.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-768x421.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-665x365.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-430x236.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-645x354.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-1068x585.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-460x252.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-600x329.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/woo-payment-gateway-extensions-500x274.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1350px) 100vw, 1350px\" /></p>\n<p>Yes, each payment gateway will likely impose its own fees, but those are often substantially lower than the ones you&#8217;d get by using a fully hosted ticketing platform. Plus, you gain all that control since you own the site and the purchasing experience!</p>\n<p>Even if you aren&#8217;t on WordPress, you could just as easily <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/support/article/how-to-install-wordpress/\">spin up a WordPress site</a> specifically for your ticket sales. That&#8217;s still a lot of control with very little investment.</p>\n<p>Wait, you even more control than that? Perfect, then you&#8217;ll love the next option.</p>\n<h3>Most control: WordPress + The Events Calendar</h3>\n<p>We&#8217;ve already covered the benefits of using WordPress for your site. Our own <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-events-calendar/\">The Events Calendar plugin</a> is designed specifically for it, plus it&#8217;s free.</p>\n<p>Why would you want to use a calendar plugin? It&#8217;s how you promote the event! That lets you create content for the event (and others) in a lovely calendar format that includes the who, what, why, where and when folks need to know.</p>\n<p>And why would you use The Events Calendar? Because it integrates seamlessly with <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-event-tickets/\">Event Tickets</a>, our free plugin that enables ticket sales for the events on your calendar. With Event Tickets, you get <a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/560364-Configuring-Tribe-Commerce-with-PayPal\">PayPal integration right out of the box</a>, plus the ability to <a href=\"https://support.theeventscalendar.com/156866-Making-Tickets\">create different types of tickets</a> at different price points. You can even schedule tickets to start and end sales on specific days at specific times. And, hey, the tickets are automatically added to the event page without having to touch anything. Sweet!</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1915704\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form.png\" alt=\"Showing tickets on an event page with four different ticket types.\" width=\"1758\" height=\"642\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form.png 1758w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-140x51.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-300x110.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-768x280.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-665x243.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-430x157.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-645x236.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-1068x390.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-460x168.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-1602x585.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-600x219.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2019/11/event-tickets-plus-ticket-form-500x183.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1758px) 100vw, 1758px\" /></p>\n<p>Oh, and if you were hoping for credit card payments, you&#8217;re covered there as well. An upgrade to <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-event-tickets-plus/\">Event Tickets Plus</a> integrates with WooCommerce to not only create tickets, but to keep the checkout on your own site and use all the payment gateway superpowers we looked at earlier.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>See, it really is all of that and a bag of chips! It really doesn&#8217;t take much to take control of your own ticket sales and cut some fees out in the process.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/sell-tickets-for-events-on-your-own-website/\">Forget the Fees: Take Control of Ticket Sales on Your Own Website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:35:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"\n	hourly	\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"\n	1	\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";O:42:\"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary\":1:{s:7:\"\0*\0data\";a:9:{s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Fri, 31 Jan 2020 10:12:36 GMT\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:34:\"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8\";s:6:\"server\";s:21:\"nginx/1.10.3 (Ubuntu)\";s:13:\"cache-control\";s:29:\"max-age=3462, must-revalidate\";s:12:\"x-powered-by\";s:27:\"PHP/7.0.33-0ubuntu0.16.04.2\";s:4:\"vary\";s:6:\"Cookie\";s:13:\"last-modified\";s:29:\"Thu, 30 Jan 2020 20:21:52 GMT\";s:4:\"etag\";s:34:\"\"5aa00d5043b2190ce203eb38a506da5b\"\";s:4:\"link\";s:66:\"<https://theeventscalendar.com/wp-json/>; rel=\"https://api.w.org/\"\";}}s:5:\"build\";s:14:\"20130911040210\";}','no'),(869,'_transient_timeout_feed_mod_0d102f2a1f4d6bc90eb8c6ffe18e56ed','1580508757','no'),(870,'_transient_feed_mod_0d102f2a1f4d6bc90eb8c6ffe18e56ed','1580465557','no'),(871,'_transient_timeout_feed_6b646ba1685199dbb7a80f9d24fbfe04','1580508757','no'),(872,'_transient_feed_6b646ba1685199dbb7a80f9d24fbfe04','a:4:{s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:3:\"rss\";a:1:{i:0;a:6: